    <item>
      <title>Quasi-Categories</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/infinity-categories/texts/quasi-categories/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 31 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/infinity-categories/texts/quasi-categories/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A quasi-category is a simplicial set in which every inner horn has a filler.&#xA;This condition ensures that higher composition exists up to coherent homotopy.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;intuition&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#intuition&#34; class=&#34;heading-anchor&#34; aria-label=&#34;Link to this section&#34;&gt;¶&lt;/a&gt;Intuition&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Vertices represent objects.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Edges represent 1-&lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Higher simplices encode higher &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; and their coherence data.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Quasi-categories are a widely used model for infinity categories because they&#xA;translate higher categorical structure into combinatorial data.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Why Infinity Categories</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/infinity-categories/texts/why-infinity-categories/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 31 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/infinity-categories/texts/why-infinity-categories/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Ordinary categories capture objects and &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt;, but many constructions in&#xA;homotopy theory require higher &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; that witness equivalences.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Infinity categories add &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; in every dimension so that composition and&#xA;equivalence are tracked up to higher homotopies, not strict equality.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This gives a setting where the objects of interest are equivalent in a flexible&#xA;way while still supporting categorical reasoning.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
